Flat profile

The flat_Profile provides a constant computational budget. It is equivalent to, simply, providing a maximum budget.

This is the only profile without a plot. It only prints the constant limit.

{% raw %}

class FlatProfile[source]

FlatProfile(max_params=3500) :: Profile

{% endraw %} {% raw %}
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
flat = FlatProfile(500)
flat.plot_profile()

Flat limit of 500
{% endraw %}

Calling the profile always returns the same value.

{% raw %} 
lim1 = int(flat(0))
lim2 = int(flat(50))
lim3 = int(flat(90))
print(f"Parameter limit at different episodes:\n0:  {lim1}\n50: {lim2}\n90: {lim3}")

Parameter limit at different episodes:
0:  500
50: 500
90: 500
{% endraw %}

Step profile

The step_profile provides an increasing computational budget by steps. The amount of steps can be chosen, as well as the initial and final limits.

{% raw %}

class StepProfile[source]

StepProfile(iterations, steps, min_params=50, max_params=3500) :: Profile

Multi-step profile from minimum to maximum

{% endraw %} {% raw %}
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
step = StepProfile(100, 3)
step.plot_profile()
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
lim1 = int(step(0))
lim2 = int(step(50))
lim3 = int(step(90))
print(f"Parameter limit at different episodes:\n0:  {lim1}\n50: {lim2}\n90: {lim3}")

Parameter limit at different episodes:
0:  50
50: 1775
90: 3500
{% endraw %}

Linear profile

The linear_profile provides a linearly increasing computational budget. The profile is a line connecting the initial and final limits.

{% raw %}

class LinearProfile[source]

LinearProfile(iterations, min_params=50, max_params=3500) :: Profile

Linear profile from the minimum of parameters to the maximum

{% endraw %} {% raw %}
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
linear = LinearProfile(100, min_params=100, max_params=300)
linear.plot_profile()
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
lim1 = int(linear(0))
lim2 = int(linear(50))
lim3 = int(linear(90))
print(f"Parameter limit at different episodes:\n0:  {lim1}\n50: {lim2}\n90: {lim3}")

Parameter limit at different episodes:
0:  100
50: 200
90: 280
{% endraw %}

Delayed linear

The delayed_linear provides a similar shape to the linear_profile with the subtlety that it delays te linear growth up to x0 and saturates it at x1. A line between x0 and x1 takes the limit from min_params to max_params.

{% raw %}

class DelayedLinear[source]

DelayedLinear(iterations, x0, x1, min_params=50, max_params=3500) :: Profile

Linear profile strarting with a plateau at the beginning

{% endraw %} {% raw %}
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
dlinear = DelayedLinear(100, 20, 80, min_params=100, max_params=500)
dlinear.plot_profile()
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
lim1 = int(dlinear(0))
lim2 = int(dlinear(50))
lim3 = int(dlinear(90))
print(f"Parameter limit at different episodes:\n0:  {lim1}\n50: {lim2}\n90: {lim3}")

Parameter limit at different episodes:
0:  100
50: 300
90: 500
{% endraw %}
